crowdsourced_yara_results.description: Detects a suspicious ELF binary with UPX compression
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit MSB executable, MIPS, MIPS-I version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, no section header

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This is a MIPS ELF binary, identified as a variant of the Mozi IoT botnet. It exhibits multiple malicious behaviors including self-propagation by exploiting common router vulnerabilities (e.g., HNAP, TR-069) using command injection payloads found in the strings. It attempts to download and execute further payloads, as evidenced by IOCs like `http://%s/Mozi.a;chmod+777+Mozi.a;/tmp/Mo`. The malware establishes persistence by creating init scripts (e.g., `/etc/init.d/S95baby.sh`), manipulates firewall rules with `iptables`, and attempts to disable system watchdogs to prevent reboots. The presence of command delimiters such as `[/atk]` and `[/dr]` indicates it receives attack and downloader commands from a C2 server.
